  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Asymmetric Information</h2>
    <p><strong>Asymmetric information</strong> occurs when one party in a transaction has more or better information than the other. This prevents markets from operating efficiently — it can lead to markets breaking down, wrong prices, or the wrong quantities being traded.</p>
    <p>The two main consequences of asymmetric information are <strong>adverse selection</strong> and <strong>moral hazard</strong>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Adverse Selection</h2>
    <p><strong>Adverse selection</strong> occurs <em>before</em> a transaction — it arises because one party has private information about their own characteristics that the other cannot observe. This causes a disproportionate number of "bad risks" or "low quality" options to participate in the market.</p>

    <h3>Classic example: The used car market (Akerlof's "Market for Lemons")</h3>
    <p>Sellers of used cars know whether their car is good or a "lemon" (poor quality), but buyers cannot easily tell the difference. Buyers therefore offer only an average price. Good-quality car owners, knowing their car is worth more, withdraw from the market. Only sellers of bad-quality cars (lemons) remain — the market is "adversely selected" toward poor quality. At the extreme, the market collapses entirely.</p>

    <h3>Other examples</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> People who know they are high-risk (sick) are more likely to buy insurance. Insurers, unable to distinguish risk levels, charge average premiums. Low-risk (healthy) people find this too expensive and drop out. The insured pool becomes increasingly high-risk, pushing premiums up further.</li>
      <li><strong>Labour markets:</strong> Firms cannot easily assess worker productivity before hiring. If wages are set at an average level, highly productive workers may seek employers who can observe their quality, leaving firms with a below-average pool of applicants.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Moral Hazard</h2>
    <p><strong>Moral hazard</strong> occurs <em>after</em> a transaction — when one party changes their behaviour because they no longer bear the full consequences of their actions, due to the other party's inability to monitor them.</p>

    <h3>Examples</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> Once insured, individuals may take less care (e.g., a fully insured driver may drive more recklessly). The insurer cannot perfectly monitor behaviour.</li>
      <li><strong>Banking:</strong> If banks believe governments will bail them out in a crisis, they may take excessive risks — the taxpayer bears the downside. This was a major factor in the 2008 financial crisis.</li>
      <li><strong>Employment:</strong> An employee whose effort is difficult to monitor may work less hard after being hired (shirking).</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Responses to Asymmetric Information</h2>

    <h3>Government responses</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Response</th><th>How it addresses the problem</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Legislation and regulation</strong></td><td>Mandatory disclosure requirements force sellers to reveal information; consumer protection laws prevent exploitation</td><td>Food labelling laws, financial product disclosure requirements</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Provision of information</strong></td><td>Government provides free information to reduce the knowledge gap</td><td>Public health campaigns, product safety ratings, school inspection reports</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Private responses</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Response</th><th>Direction of information</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Signalling</strong></td><td>The informed party sends a credible signal to the less-informed party</td><td>Job applicants use university degrees as signals of ability; firms offer warranties to signal product quality</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Screening</strong></td><td>The less-informed party gathers information by designing mechanisms that reveal private information</td><td>Insurers offer multiple policy options at different prices to reveal customers' risk levels; employers use probationary periods or interviews to learn about workers</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Asymmetric information: one party knows more than the other</li>
      <li>Adverse selection: before transaction; disproportionate "bad risks" participate</li>
      <li>Moral hazard: after transaction; behaviour changes due to reduced consequences</li>
      <li>Government: legislation, regulation, information provision</li>
      <li>Private: signalling (informed party signals) vs screening (uninformed party investigates)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-10">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
