  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions <span class="hl-badge">HL</span></div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Explain the difference between adverse selection and moral hazard. Use the insurance industry as a context for both.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <strong>Adverse selection</strong> occurs before the insurance contract is signed. High-risk individuals know they are high-risk and are more likely to seek insurance. If the insurer cannot distinguish risk levels and charges average premiums, low-risk individuals may not buy insurance (too expensive for them), leaving the pool increasingly high-risk — the insurer has "adversely selected" its customers. <strong>Moral hazard</strong> occurs after the contract. Once insured, the insured party may take less care (e.g., leave valuables unattended, drive recklessly) because the insurer bears the cost of any loss. The insurer cannot fully monitor behaviour, creating the moral hazard.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Distinguish between "signalling" and "screening" as private responses to asymmetric information. Give one example of each.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <strong>Signalling</strong> is when the party with more information sends a credible signal to the less-informed party. For example, a job applicant obtains a university degree to signal ability to employers — the degree is valuable as a signal because it is costly to obtain, so only genuinely able candidates find it worthwhile. <strong>Screening</strong> is when the less-informed party designs mechanisms to reveal private information. For example, an insurance company offers several policy options with different premium/excess combinations — high-risk customers will choose low-excess (high premium) policies while low-risk customers choose high-excess, revealing their risk type to the insurer.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

